## The Prediction Market Boom Is Drawing New Traders

Prediction markets have entered the mainstream, and [Polymarket](https://polymarket.com/?r=POLYTips) sits at the center of that explosion. With markets like the US-Iran peace deal negotiations seeing over $21 million in total volume and the Hantavirus pandemic question holding nearly $1.8 million in liquidity, real money is flowing into forecasting real-world events. For newcomers watching these numbers and wondering how to participate, the barrier to entry is lower than you might expect. Understanding how to trade on Polymarket effectively, however, requires more than just creating an account and clicking buttons.

The platform operates differently from traditional exchanges or sports betting sites. Polymarket uses a continuous double auction model where you are trading shares against other participants, not against the house. This fundamental difference shapes everything from how you should think about pricing to when you should enter and exit positions. Getting comfortable with these mechanics early will save you from expensive lessons later.

## Setting Up Your Account and Making Your First Deposit

Creating a Polymarket account starts with connecting a cryptocurrency wallet. The platform primarily operates on the Polygon network, which means you will need USDC (a stablecoin pegged to the US dollar) to fund your trading. If you are coming from traditional finance, think of USDC as digital dollars that move on blockchain rails. The process involves either depositing crypto directly or using one of Polymarket's fiat on-ramp partners to convert dollars into USDC.

The on-ramp options have improved significantly in 2026, making it possible to fund an account with a credit card or bank transfer in many jurisdictions. Transaction fees vary by method, with direct crypto deposits typically being cheapest and card payments carrying the highest percentage fee. Starting with a modest amount makes sense for learning purposes. You do not need thousands of dollars to understand how the platform works, and the education you gain from a few hundred dollars of trading experience is worth far more than theoretical knowledge.

## Understanding Shares, Prices, and How Payouts Work

Every Polymarket question resolves to either Yes or No, and each outcome has tradeable shares priced between zero and one dollar. If a market shows Yes shares at 65 cents, the crowd collectively estimates a 65 percent probability of that outcome occurring. When the event resolves, winning shares pay out exactly one dollar each, while losing shares become worthless. The math is straightforward but the implications are profound.

Buying Yes shares at 65 cents means you profit 35 cents per share if the event happens and lose 65 cents if it does not. Your potential return scales inversely with the market's confidence. This is why experienced traders often look for situations where they believe the true probability differs meaningfully from the market price. A market priced at 50 percent offers even risk-reward on both sides, while a market priced at 90 percent requires high conviction to bet against but offers substantial returns if you are right.

