## Placing Trades and Managing Your Orders

The actual mechanics of placing a trade involve selecting your side (Yes or No), entering your stake, and confirming the transaction. Polymarket offers both market orders that execute immediately at current prices and limit orders that only fill if the market reaches your specified price. Limit orders give you more control but require patience, while market orders provide immediacy at the cost of potentially worse execution on larger positions.

Position management deserves careful attention. Unlike sports betting where you wait for a single resolution, prediction market positions can be exited at any time by selling your shares back to the market. If you bought Yes shares at 40 cents and the price rises to 70 cents, you can sell for a 30 cent profit without waiting for the event to resolve. This liquidity creates opportunities but also temptations. Many new traders either hold positions too long hoping for more gains or exit too early when prices move against them briefly. Developing discipline around when to take profits and when to cut losses is a skill that separates profitable traders from unprofitable ones.

## Learning from the Sharpest Traders on the Platform

One advantage of trading on a transparent blockchain-based platform is that all positions are visible. Sophisticated tools now exist to track what experienced traders are doing. The [top 50 Polymarket traders](/best-polymarket-traders-to-follow-2026/) have been identified by verified profit and loss, and their movements provide valuable signal about how sharp money views various markets. When multiple elite traders independently take the same position, it creates what is called a [convergence signal](/what-is-a-convergence-signal/), suggesting that informed analysis is pointing in a particular direction.

This does not mean blindly copying trades. Context matters enormously. A trader might be hedging a larger position elsewhere, expressing a short-term view rather than a prediction about final resolution, or operating with information and time horizons that differ from yours. But watching how successful traders size their positions, which markets they focus on, and how they adjust as new information emerges teaches lessons that no guide can fully capture. Think of it as an apprenticeship where you observe masters at work while developing your own judgment.

## Building Your Edge Over Time

Trading on [Polymarket](https://polymarket.com/?r=POLYTips) successfully requires developing genuine expertise in the domains you trade. The traders who consistently profit tend to specialize. Some focus on politics and develop deep knowledge of electoral dynamics and polling interpretation. Others concentrate on crypto markets where they already have information advantages. Still others trade geopolitical events because their professional backgrounds give them insight into how international relations actually function.

The worst approach is treating prediction markets like a casino where you bet on whatever looks interesting. The best approach is identifying areas where you can realistically know more than the average market participant and focusing your capital there. This might mean trading fewer markets but trading them with higher conviction. It might mean waiting for specific situations where the market appears to be mispricing information you understand well. The goal is not to trade constantly but to trade well when the opportunities align with your knowledge.

